Mariupol going through ‘Armageddon’ as Russia fires on residential areas, mayor says
Return to menu
By Zina Pozen and Hannah Knowles 5:03 p.m.
Link copied
Link

The mayor of Mariupol said Thursday that people in his blockaded Ukrainian port city were going through “Armageddon” and “two days of hell” as Russian forces fired on residential areas.

“Every 30 minutes, the city of Mariupol was visited by aviation, which worked in residential areas, killing civilians: old people, women, children,” Mayor Vadym Boichenko said in a video, describing Thursday’s devastation. “This is the greatness of the Russian army.”

Accusing Russia of “genocide” and calling Russian President Vladimir Putin a “terrorist,” Boichenko said 400,000 residents of Mariupol are being held captive, waiting for a “humanitarian corridor” to materialize. Ukrainian officials have repeatedly accused Russia of violating temporary cease-fires meant to clear the way for civilian evacuations and delivery of supplies.

Leaders have also warned for days of a humanitarian crisis in southern Mariupol, saying Russian forces have cut off entrances and exits and left the city without much water, electricity, heat or mobile communication. On Wednesday, at least three people were killed and 17 were injured there in a strike on a maternity hospital .

Ukraine’s battered Mariupol, reeling from hospital strike, says Russia’s assault continues as bodies pile up

Speaking in a video the Mariupol City Council posted to Telegram on Thursday, Boichenko said “humanitarian cargo” was unable to enter the city for a sixth day. He said there remained no viable path for evacuation, despite Russian promises.

“As we try to get through, we run into mines, we hit tanks, we fall under the hail,” he said. “A struggle for the life of our city” was underway Thursday, the mayor said, led by Ukraine’s top officials.

“Work is underway to make this corridor, so that the cargo that needs to reach Mariupol could reach it,” Boichenko said. “I am sure it will.”
