Interpol rejects calls to suspend Russia, says data-sharing must continue
Return to menu
By Hannah Knowles 3:50 p.m.
Link copied
Link

Interpol on Thursday rejected calls to suspend Russia’s access to the policing consortium’s data on crimes around the world, calling neutrality “fundamental” to its work even when some of its 195 member countries are in conflict.

“As long as the INTERPOL network can assist in the rescue of one child abuse victim, the prevention of one terrorist attack or the identification of one missing person, it is its duty to ensure that lines of communication remain open,” the international group’s leadership said in a statement.

Officials in Australia, Canada, the United Kingdom, the United States and New Zealand — the members of the “Five Eyes” intelligence alliance — had urged Interpol to “decide this week on the immediate suspension of Russia’s access,” according to the U.S. Justice Department. U.K. Home Secretary Priti Patel argued that Russia’s invasion of Ukraine was a “direct threat to the safety of individuals and to international law enforcement cooperation.”

But Interpol’s General Secretariat, the central body that runs the cooperative, said its mandate “does not include issuing sanctions or taking punitive measures.” It said many law enforcement leaders expressed concerns about the consequences of halting information-sharing and said war creates fertile ground for exploitation, trafficking, smuggling and other crimes.

This year, Interpol said, almost 60,000 checks against its databases have referenced data from Russia.

“INTERPOL was created to ensure the widest possible law enforcement cooperation, including between countries where diplomatic relations do not exist,” the General Secretariat said.

The group said its secretary general is working to prevent misuse of Interpol’s channels to target people in Ukraine and beyond. It noted that Ukraine has disconnected from its network. Now all of Moscow’s requests for international cooperation must go through the General Secretariat “to be checked for compliance,” Interpol leadership said.
