Drone footage appears to show ambush on a Russian battalion north of Kyiv
Return to menu
By Louisa Loveluck and Elyse Samuels 3:13 p.m.
Link copied
Link

Drone footage published Thursday by Ukraine’s Defense Ministry appears to show an ambush on a column of Russian armored vehicles north of Kyiv.

In the footage from Brovary, a city 15 miles from the capital, several vehicles are attacked, sparking panic among the battalion’s drivers. Black tracks are left etched on the road as some try to swerve and escape.

The footage was verified by The Washington Post and analyzed by Ukraine Weapons Tracker, a Twitter account analyzing the types of arms and equipment being utilized in the war, and Rob Lee, a senior fellow at the Foreign Policy Research Institute.

    Ліквідовано командира полку окупанта полковника Захарова

    Під час ведення бойових дій в Броварського району Київської області зазнала значних втрат в особовому складі та техніці бальйонно-тактична група (БТГр) 6 танкового полку (Чебаркуль) 90 танкової дивізії ЦВО. pic.twitter.com/BJUHcskuWG
    — Defence intelligence of Ukraine (@DI_Ukraine) March 10, 2022 

The Ukrainian Defense Ministry said that the battalion’s commander, which it identified as a Col. Zakharov, was killed in the attack. No further details were provided.

The video, which bears the watermark of the Azov brigade, a far-right armed group that forms part of Ukraine’s National Guard, was edited to include an audio recording purporting to contain the emergency call of a Russian soldier in the aftermath of one of the attacks.

“The head of the cortege got into a trap,” the voice says. “The regiment commander died. Figuring out about the others now.”

The Ukrainian Defense Ministry did not specify where the recording came from, and it could not be independently verified.
Berlin erects tents for refugees but says it’s not the beginning of a tent city
Return to menu
By Vanessa Guinan-Bank 2:46 p.m.
Link copied
Link

BERLIN — Now that more than 2.3 million refugees have fled Ukraine, with potentially more than a million still to come, the question of how smoothly they can be absorbed into destination countries looms large.

Some observers expressed concern that tents erected in Berlin this week were a worrying sign — perhaps the beginning of long-term tent cities. But Berlin officials said the tents are primarily to help people stay warm while waiting their turn to register as refugees at the main arrival center. People have been staying one night at most, officials said, before buses take them to shelters across the country.

While Poland has received the greatest number of refugees, officials in Berlin estimate that they are registering thousands of new arrivals each day.

“It’s a destination that many people know and head for, especially those who do not have familial connections or networks in Poland, where many Ukrainians have lived before,” said Monika Hebbinghaus, a spokeswoman for the state office of refugee affairs.

The European Union is extending up to three years of “temporary protection” to Ukrainian nationals, allowing them to work and access public services while bypassing the usual lengthy asylum process. Some refugees from Ukraine are staying with family or friends already living in the E.U. But those without connections, along with non-Ukrainians who fled the war, are seeking shelter under the structures initially built for Syrian refugees in 2015.
Bolton says Russia didn’t invade Ukraine sooner because ‘Putin saw Trump doing a lot of his work for him’
Return to menu
By Timothy Bella 2:45 p.m.
Link copied
Link

Former national security adviser John Bolton claimed that one of the reasons Russian President Vladimir Putin did not invade Ukraine sooner was because of Bolton’s old boss, former president Donald Trump.

In an interview with SiriusXM’s Julie Mason, Bolton, who has gone from Trump official to critic, said the world would be in “a lot worse shape” at this point of the invasion if Trump had gone through with his threat to withdraw the United States from NATO. Trump has recently sought to rewrite history on his approach to NATO and Ukraine, The Washington Post’s Glenn Kessler wrote on the Fact Checker .

“I think one of the reasons Putin did not move during Trump’s term in office was he saw the president’s hostility in NATO,” Bolton said late Wednesday. “It was widely reported in American media, and to Putin’s mind, it’s a binary proposition, a weaker NATO is a stronger Russia.”

Bolton, who recently said Trump “ barely knew where Ukraine was ,” then went one step further in his assessment of why Putin did not launch his invasion earlier.

“Putin saw Trump doing a lot of his work for him and thought maybe in a second term, Trump would make good on his desire to get out of NATO and then it would just ease Putin’s path just that much more,” he said.
Rep. Madison Cawthorn calls Zelensky a ‘thug,’ says Ukrainian government is ‘incredibly evil’
Return to menu
By Felicia Sonmez and Mariana Alfaro 2:44 p.m.
Link copied
Link

Rep. Madison Cawthorn (R-N.C.) recently called Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky a “thug” and said the Ukrainian government is “incredibly evil,” in remarks that are at odds with the broad bipartisan support for Ukraine among American lawmakers and the public amid Russia’s invasion.

“Remember that Zelensky is a thug. Remember that the Ukrainian government is incredibly corrupt, and it is incredibly evil, and it has been pushing woke ideologies,” Cawthorn told supporters at a recent event in North Carolina, according to video published Thursday by Raleigh-based TV station WRAL .

Cawthorn, 26, is in his first term in the House and is a vocal supporter of former president Donald Trump, who has recently praised Russian President Vladimir Putin’s handling of the invasion as “genius” and “savvy.”

The congressman’s comments were first reported Wednesday night by Republican strategist Karl Rove in a Wall Street Journal op-ed.

In a statement, Cawthorn spokesman Luke Ball said the lawmaker was referring to pro-Ukraine misinformation.

“The Congressman was expressing his displeasure at how foreign leaders, including Zelensky, had recently used false propaganda to entice America into becoming involved in an overseas conflict,” Ball said. “He supports Ukraine and the Ukrainian President’s efforts to defend their country against Russian aggression, but does not want America drawn into another conflict through emotional manipulation.”
